mmodified in, tourism settings and considers language practices and discourse as a way of constructing identities, boundaries and places. It also reflects on academic practice and economic dynamics in a field that is characterised by social inequalities and injustice, and tourism as the world's largest industry enacting dynamic communicative, social and cultural transformations. The book will appeal to both undergraduate and postgraduate students of tourism studies, linguistics, literature, cultural history and anthropology, as well as researchers and professionals in these fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jul 2020) 4aSociolinguistics of tourism. 4acultural entanglements. 4aglobal south. 4alinguistic entanglements. 4alinguistic representation. 4apostcolonial. 4atouristic performance. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh1 aMietzner, Angelika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStorch, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.21832/978184541679940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781845416799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781845416799.jpg  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK